j = \frac{I}{A} = nev_d = \sigma E

\sigma = conductivity, E = electric field

Microscopic Ohm's law: \vec{j} = \sigma \vec{E}

R = \rho \frac{l}{A}

\rho = resistivity (\Omega \cdot \text{m}), l = length, A = cross-sectional area

Also: \rho = \frac{m}{ne^2\tau}

\frac{1}{R_{eq}} = \frac{1}{R_1} + \frac{1}{R_2} + \cdots + \frac{1}{R_n}

For two resistors: R_{eq} = \frac{R_1 R_2}{R_1 + R_2}

Same voltage across all resistors.

**KCL (Junction Rule):** \sum I_{\text{in}} = \sum I_{\text{out}}

**KVL (Loop Rule):** \sum \Delta V = 0 \text{ (around any closed loop)}

Sign conventions:
- Through R in direction of I: \Delta V = -IR
- Through cell from - to +: \Delta V = +E

\frac{P}{Q} = \frac{R}{S}

Or equivalently: PS = QR

At balance, galvanometer current I_g = 0 and points B, D are equipotential.

\frac{X}{R} = \frac{l}{100 - l}

X = R \times \frac{l}{100 - l}

X = unknown resistance, R = known resistance, l = null-point length (cm) from left end

P = VI = I^2R = \frac{V^2}{R}

Unit: Watt (W) = J/s

Energy: 1 \text{ kWh} = 3.6 \times 10^6 \text{ J}

H = I^2Rt = VIt = \frac{V^2}{R}t

Heat in calories: H_{\text{cal}} = \frac{I^2Rt}{4.18}

For temperature rise: I^2Rt = ms\Delta T

